    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "aa55d9ce_2ea7d27b",
        "filename": "niagara/cmd/machine_manager/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-03T12:36:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That would mean either the machine talks to task scheduler to tell it it has started or machine manager passes this along, neither of which seems clean to me.\n\nWhat did you have in mind?",
      "parentUuid": "f8d88c15_7414c5a4",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 126
      },
      "revId": "72b464829cc692fc3e4f69423fdbd2f64eab1f04",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9777dc01_3f235040",
        "filename": "niagara/cmd/machine_manager/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-03T12:43:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Machine manager is already notifying task scheduler when machine(s) are available to perform work, so it seems okay to have it also notify task scheduler when a machine has started a task (also finished, or gone offline while running, etc).  I like having task scheduler be the only entity which is writing to the task DB.",
      "parentUuid": "aa55d9ce_2ea7d27b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 126
      },
      "revId": "72b464829cc692fc3e4f69423fdbd2f64eab1f04",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "b1f7cb16_dcf852d8",
        "filename": "niagara/cmd/machine_manager/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-03T13:03:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Machine manager \"notifies\" task scheduler that amachine is ready by writing to Firestore. (You\u0027ll notice that emulated_task_scheduler has no pubsub client).\n\nIs granting task scheduler exclusive write access to the task DB a must-have?",
      "parentUuid": "9777dc01_3f235040",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 126
      },
      "revId": "72b464829cc692fc3e4f69423fdbd2f64eab1f04",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "40d10cf4_74899e48",
        "filename": "niagara/cmd/machine_manager/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-03T13:23:40Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh, right - so if task scheduler is already watching the machines collection, and if the machine has a CurrentTask field, then task scheduler will already see that a machine has started running the task, and there\u0027s no need for any notification or for machine manager to write to the tasks DB.  I would strongly prefer that task scheduler has exclusive write access to its own DB, unless there\u0027s no other way to do it.  I like the separation of concerns too: machine manager only deals with machines, task scheduler only deals with tasks, etc.",
      "parentUuid": "b1f7cb16_dcf852d8",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 126
      },
      "revId": "72b464829cc692fc3e4f69423fdbd2f64eab1f04",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fb84f995_199b3ebb",
        "filename": "niagara/cmd/machine_manager/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-03T13:34:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I\u0027m not sure it\u0027s feasible to completely separate the two. Notice in the existing schema, task scheduler writes \"assigned\" to the machine status, which makes sure task scheduler does not try to assign it another task in the future.\n\nI could add in a pubsub channel between task scheduler and machine manager, but that seems like an unnecessary hop at the moment, and I\u0027m going to prefer simplicity until complexity is necessitated.",
      "parentUuid": "40d10cf4_74899e48",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 126
      },
      "revId": "72b464829cc692fc3e4f69423fdbd2f64eab1f04",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "573bc681_752e7c7b",
        "filename": "niagara/cmd/machine_manager/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-03T13:57:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Maybe I\u0027m not understanding - why does task scheduler need to update the machine status?  This is the flow I\u0027m imagining:\n\n- Machine sends pubsub message indicating that it is online and idle.\n- Machine Manager updates the machine DB entry for this machine.\n- Task Scheduler is watching the machine DB and notices that the machine is free.  It updates the task DB, marking a task as being assigned to the machine in question.\n- Machine is watching the task DB for tasks assigned to its ID. It notices that the task has been assigned to it, starts running the task and sends a pubsub message indicating such.\n- Machine Manager updates the machine DB entry for the machine, indicating that it is running the task.\n- Task scheduler is watching the machine DB, sees that the task has been started on the machine, and updates the task DB accordingly.\n- Machine finishes running the task and sends a pubsub message indicating such.\n- Machine manager updates the machine DB entry indicating that the machine is now free and has completed the task with a particular result status.\n- Task scheduler notices the change in the machine DB and updates the task DB accordingly.",
      "parentUuid": "fb84f995_199b3ebb",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 126
      },
      "revId": "72b464829cc692fc3e4f69423fdbd2f64eab1f04",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ae0597bf_1a5b41e6",
        "filename": "niagara/cmd/machine_manager/main.go",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-03T14:18:07Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "One scenario to consider:\n1) Task scheduler updates the task DB, and then crashes. I envisioned that when the task scheduler reboots, it would want to poll for all idle machines, so it can continue working. In this case there is a race condition between Task scheduler rebooting and fetching all idle machines and the rest of the flow marking the machine as busy, which could allow for multiple tasks assigned to the same machine. \n\nI think I had also envisioned some checking going on by machine_manager to make sure that a machine which said it is starting a task actually was assigned that task, but that may be unnecessary.\n\nI\u0027d rather not leave the race condition between the two collections (which is fixed if task scheduler updates tasks and machines in a transaction), WDYT?",
      "parentUuid": "573bc681_752e7c7b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 126
      },
      "revId": "72b464829cc692fc3e4f69423fdbd2f64eab1f04",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
